        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>
We have chosen the largest possible bandwidth in order to measure also the broad absorption component of the CO isotopes, as well as the CO itself which influences the local continuum of the isotopes. It results in a spectral resolution of 1.1 MHz,  which is enough to well sample the FWHM 
of the line on Neptune and to perform the line velocity correction in the post-processing, as accurately as possible.

</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>
In order to obtain the best signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) for the detection of the weak isotopes,
we ask for the compact configurations C36-1 which provides a beam of 1.0" in band 7 (or C36-3 at 0.4" allowing night observations).  
With such beams, the Neptunes disk (~2.2") will be slightly resolved.  
To recover the maximum flux, we plan to analyze the data by either  
i) fitting the data in the UV-plane to derive disk-averaged flux,  
ii) applying a beam tapering in order to obtain a 2.2" beam and integrate the flux in the image. 

Our simulations indicates that we do not expect any flux losses due to short spacing, since at our highest 354 GHz frequency,  
the C36-1 or  C36-3 configuration has a maximum angular scale (MAS) 3 times larger than the planets apparent diameter.

Note that in the Config C36-3, we expect a small loss in sentivity (~ 25%) because there are less short baselines. Nevertheless, taking into account the estimated SNR &gt;20 on the weaker lines, this will be still acceptable.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>
The narrow emission (FWHM ~10 MHz) lines probes mainly the stratosphere. The lowest pressure probed in the stratosphere is ~0.1-1 mbar; 
at these levels, the lines are significantly broadened by the velocity smearing due to the planet's rotation (+/- 2.66 km/s, i.e. 4 MHz).  
A spectral resolution of 4 MHz is hereafter considered for the time estimates.

Our simulations of the line intensities assuming terrestrial isotopic ratios are presented in Figs. 2. The expected line intensities 
are of 40 mJy/4MHz/Beam for the HC15N line, 45 mJy/4MHz/beam for the C18O line, and 240 mJy/4MHz/beam for the 13CO line. 
In order to have a robust SNR of ~20 on the weakest HC15N lines, and taking into account the HC15N line is observable in both setups, 
we ask to spend 0.7 hour in Setup-1 (i.e. a sensitivity of 2.5 mJy/4MHz/Beam) and 0.7 hour in Setup-2. 
The corresponding SNR for the other lines will be ~13 for C18O, ~80 for 13CO. 

We have chosen the largest possible bandwidth in order to measure also the broad absorption component of the CO isotopes, as well as the CO itself which influences the local continuum of the isotopes. It results in a spectral resolution of 1.1 MHz,  which is enough to well sample the FWHM 
of the line on Neptune and to perform the line velocity correction in the post-processing, as accurately as possible.

Based on our experience on cycle 0 Venus observations in band 7 (the rms on the line/continuum measurement can reach 0.01%), 
a standard RF bandpass measurement of 10 minutes on a strong quasar will be enough to measure accurately 
the weak but narrow line/continuum ratio on C18O (0.3%)  and still more easily 13CO (2%).
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
