at these levels, the lines are significantly broadened by the velocity smearing due to the planet's rotation (+/- 2.66 km/s, i.e. 4 MHz).  
A spectral resolution of 4 MHz is hereafter considered for the time estimates.

Our simulations of the line intensities assuming terrestrial isotopic ratios are presented in Figs. 2. The expected line intensities 
are of 40 mJy/4MHz/Beam for the HC15N line, and 120 mJy/4MHz/beam for the H13CN line.  
For the CO and HCN main species, strong fluxes, larger than 8 Jy/4MHz/beam are predicted. 
In order to have a robust SNR of ~20 on the weakest HC15N lines, and taking into account the HC15N line is observable in both setups, 
we ask to spend 0.7 hour in Setup-1 (i.e. a sensitivity of 2.5 mJy/4MHz/Beam) and 0.7 hour in Setup-2. 
The corresponding SNR for the other line will be ~50 for H13CN. Finally the SNR for CO and HCN will be &gt; 3000.

We have chosen the largest possible bandwidth in order to measure also the broad absorption component of the CO isotopes, as well as the CO itself which influences the local continuum of the isotopes. It results in a spectral resolution of 1.1 MHz,  which is enough to well sample the FWHM 
of the line on Neptune and to perform the line velocity correction in the post-processing, as accurately as possible.

Based on our experience on cycle 0 Venus observations in band 7 (the rms on the line/continuum measurement can reach 0.01%), 
a standard RF bandpass measurement of 10 minutes on a strong quasar will be enough to measure accurately 
the weak but narrow line/continuum ratio on HC15N (0.3%)  and still more easily H13CN (0.7%).





</prj:justificationText>
